TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Catastrophe Model of Employee Withdrawal Leading to Low Job Performance, High Absenteeism, and Job Turnover During the First Year of Employment
AU  - Sheridan, John E.
Y1  - 1985/03/01
PY  - 1985
DA  - 1985/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256063
DO  - 10.5465/256063
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 88
EP  - 109
VL  - 28
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - A catastrophe model of employee withdrawal indicates that declining job performance, absenteeism, and turnover are discontinuous behavioral outcomes of the same withdrawal phenomenon arising from varying levels of job tension and group cohesion. The advantages of using catastrophe models to describe the temporal changes in employee withdrawal over a relatively short time period are discussed.
AB  - A catastrophe model of employee withdrawal indicates that declining job performance, absenteeism, and turnover are discontinuous behavioral outcomes of the same withdrawal phenomenon arising from varying levels of job tension and group cohesion. The advantages of using catastrophe models to describe the temporal changes in employee withdrawal over a relatively short time period are discussed.
