TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Effects of Framing and Negotiator Overconfidence on Bargaining Behaviors and Outcomes
AU  - Neale, Margaret A.
AU  - Bazerman, Max H.
Y1  - 1985/03/01
PY  - 1985
DA  - 1985/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256060
DO  - 10.5465/256060
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 34
EP  - 49
VL  - 28
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Two systematic biases?the framing of conflict and negotiator overconfidence?are suggested as possible influences on negotiator behaviors. To investigate these biases, 100 subjects were asked to negotiate a five-issue contract under controlled conditions. Results indicated that (1) a positive frame led to more concessionary behaviors and successful performances than a negative frame and (2) realistically confident subjects exhibited more concessionary behaviors and successful performances than subjects who were overconfident. Implications of the results of this study for third-party intervention and the training of negotiators are discussed.
AB  - Two systematic biases?the framing of conflict and negotiator overconfidence?are suggested as possible influences on negotiator behaviors. To investigate these biases, 100 subjects were asked to negotiate a five-issue contract under controlled conditions. Results indicated that (1) a positive frame led to more concessionary behaviors and successful performances than a negative frame and (2) realistically confident subjects exhibited more concessionary behaviors and successful performances than subjects who were overconfident. Implications of the results of this study for third-party intervention and the training of negotiators are discussed.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/256060
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/256060
Y2  - 2026/04/24
